    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-02-19T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-02-19T12:00:00-05:00" n="399"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d399">
                <head>399. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission to the United
                        Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d399fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, POL 19 SW AFR/<gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>. Confidential.
                        Repeated to London and Cape Town.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-02-19T12:00:00-05:00">February 19, 1963,
                        noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3069. Subj: Southwest Africa.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>We spoke to UKDel along lines <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss>
                            2123<note n="1" xml:id="d399fn1">Telegram 2123, February 11, instructed
                                <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> to undertake, in concert with
                            the United Kingdom, a sustained effort to convince the South African
                            Government that its own interests, as well as those of the Free World,
                            required it to seek a political accommodation with the world community
                            regarding the Mandated Territory of South West Africa—ideally before the
                            International Court of Justice rendered its decision in late 1963 or
                            early 1964. (Ibid.)</note> Feb 18. Campbell (<gloss target="#t_UK1"
                            >UK</gloss>) said question already raised in London. He understood
                            <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> and US Embs in Capetown would be in
                        consultation on what would be best approach to South Africans and gave
                        impression joint or parallel action depended upon this discussion. (<gloss
                            target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> apparently anxious initial consideration be
                        in Capetown.)</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We told Campbell we also intended raise problem with <gloss
                            target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> this week in order to ascertain <gloss
                            target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss>’s plans re establishing <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> presence in <gloss target="#t_SWA1"
                            >SWA</gloss> in accordance with <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> Res.
                        Campbell said he would appreciate <pb facs="0653" n="625" xml:id="pg_625"/>
                        report from US on this discussion. (Important that whatever steps we take re
                            <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> presence be in accord with <gloss
                            target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss>’s plans.) So far we know of nothing other
                        than appointment of technical assistance rep but it may be he has other
                        ideas in mind.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Besides general approaches to South Africa re problem they face with
                            <gloss target="#t_ICJ1">ICJ</gloss> opinion and on <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> presence, Campbell expressed desire for
                        further US-<gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> talks here on <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> tactical issues we likely to face (including
                        presumably both apartheid problem in South Africa, on which UKDel has
                        already expressed concern, and <gloss target="#t_SWA1">SWA</gloss>
                        issue).</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Plimpton</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
